This paper is likely to belong to the Robotics (cs.RO) sub-category as it proposes a framework for bipedal gait pattern generation. The use of Nonlinear Model Predictive Control (NMPC) and the consideration of footstep location, CoM vertical motion, upper-body inclination, and joint torques are all common topics in robotics research. 

The Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category is also likely as the paper deals with control strategies for maintaining balance while walking under dynamic disturbances. 

The Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category is a possibility as the paper proposes a framework for generating versatile walking patterns based on terrain information input. 

The Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category is also a possibility as the paper may involve learning algorithms for generating walking patterns. 

The Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition (cs.CV) sub-category is less likely but still possible as the paper may involve image processing techniques for terrain analysis.
